[1] Germany: new deaths
Date: Mon 30 May 2011
Source: Forbes [edited]
http://blogs.forbes.com/williampentland/2011/05/30/deadly-cucumbers-kill-14-in-germany-death-toll-still-rising/


More than 2 weeks after a food poisoning epidemic broke out in
northern Germany, at least 14 people have been reported dead and
hundreds have fallen sick from an extremely dangerous strain of the
_E. coli_ bacterium found on imported cucumbers.

The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control described the
outbreak "one of the largest worldwide and the largest ever reported
in Germany."

German authorities urged people to avoid eating raw vegetables after
traces of the bacteria were found on organic cucumbers last week [week
of 23 May 2011]. The vegetables were apparently imported from Spain.

The number of confirmed and suspected cases has reached 1200,
according to media reports. The outbreak has hit countries that
include Britain, Denmark, Sweden, and the Netherlands, but most of the
cases appear to involve people who had recently traveled to or from
Germany.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The overall case number as well as the number of those affected by
HUS and the total death count continue to rise. It remains to be
determined where and how the contamination of the cucumbers (and any
other contaminated salad ingredients) occurred related to this unusual
VTEC serotype that is eae-negative and possesses a very antimicrobial
reistance phenotype. - Mod.LL]

******
[2] Source of pathogen still unclear
Date: Sun 29 May 2011
Source: RTE News [edited]
http://www.rte.ie/news/2011/0529/ecoli.html


German authorities have warned that the source of an outbreak of VTEC
_E. coli_ blamed for 10 [now 14] deaths and hundreds of people falling
ill, has yet to be pinpointed.

"Until experts in Germany and Spain are able to positively identify
the source of the pathogen, general warnings about vegetables remain
valid," consumer minister Ilse Aiger told the Bild am Sonntag
newspaper. "The relevant authorities are doing all they can to clear
this up, nationally and internationally."

The epicentre of the outbreak has been in northern Germany, with
hundreds of other suspected cases reported, but cases have also been
reported in France, Sweden, Denmark, Britain, Switzerland, Austria,
and The Netherlands.

Suspicion has so far turned on Spain, with the European Commission
saying on Fri 27 May 2011, that organic cucumbers grown in the
southern provinces of Almeria and Malaga are suspected as a source of
the outbreak. Southern Spanish authorities said yesterday, 28 May
2011, they had introduced restrictions on 2 distributors suspected of
exporting tainted cucumbers. Andalusia's regional council said suspect
batches had been withdrawn pending tests.

But the European Commission also said that a batch of cucumbers
originating either in The Netherlands or in Denmark, and traded in
Germany, was also under investigation.

--
