******
[4] Sweden: 1st death outside Germany
Date: Tue 31 May 2011
Source: Beaumont Enterprise, Associated Press (AP) report [edited]
http://www.beaumontenterprise.com/news/article/E-coli-outbreak-kills-woman-in-Sweden-1402453.php


An additional 2 deaths linked to a bacterial outbreak in Europe
blamed on tainted vegetables were reported Tue 31 May 2011, including
the 1st outside Germany, as the number of people falling ill continued
to rise. The deaths brought to 16 the total number of fatalities
linked to the _E. coli_ outbreak, with northwestern Germany the
hardest-hit region.

Hospital officials in Boras, Sweden, announced the death of woman in
her 50s who was admitted on 29 May 2011 after a trip to Germany. In
Paderborn, Germany, the local council said an 87-year-old woman who
also suffered from other ailments had died.

In Germany, the national disease control center said 373 people were
sick with the most serious form of the outbreak, hemolytic-uremic
syndrome, or HUS, a rare complication arising from an infection most
commonly associated with certain toxic-producing _E. coli_. That
figure was up from the 329 reported Mon 30 May 2011.

Susanne Glasmacher, a spokeswoman for the Robert Koch Institute, said
another 796 people have been affected by the enterohemorrhagic _E.
coli_, also known as EHEC, bacteria -- making a total of more than
1150 people infected. Hundreds of people also have been sickened in
other European countries, but until Tue 31 May 2011, Germany had seen
the only deaths.

Germany's Federal Institute for Risk Assessment is still warning
consumers to avoid all cucumbers, lettuces, and raw tomatoes as the
outbreak is investigated.

European Union officials have said that German authorities identified
cucumbers from the Spanish regions of Almeria and Malaga as possible
sources of contamination and that a 3rd suspect batch, originating
either in the Netherlands or in Denmark and traded in Germany, is also
under investigation.

They have also noted, however, that the transport chain is long, and
the cucumbers from Spain could have been contaminated at any point
along the route.

The Danish Veterinary and Food Administration said Tue 31 May 2011,
that no traces of EHEC bacteria were found in tests conducted over the
weekend.

"There is therefore nothing that indicates that Danish cucumbers are
the source of the serious _E. coli_ outbreak that has infected several
patients in Germany, Denmark, and Sweden," the agency said.

[Byline: David Rising, Karl Ritter, Malin Rising]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[This posting reports the 1st death outside Germany but acquired
there, associated with the quite large and still growing outbreak. As
the number of cases continues to rise, one wonders if this is related
to some cases with a longer incubation period, the inability of
getting the cucumbers and other salad vegetables off the market and
out of people's homes, or continued contamination.

Again, the method and site of the contamination remains unclear. -
Mod.LL]

******
[5] Spain, Austria, Britain, Netherlands, USA: possible 1st cases ex
Germany
Date: Tue 31 May 2011
Source: Deutsche Presse Agentur (DPA) [edited]
http://www.monstersandcritics.com/news/health/news/article_1642552.php/First-possible-E-coli-case-reported-in-Spain


A 1st possible case of _E. coli_ infection has been discovered in
Spain, Basque health officials said on Tue 31 May 2011.

Germany has blamed Spanish cucumbers for the _E. coli_ [O104]
outbreak that has claimed 14 [now 15 in Germany and 1 in Sweden -
Mod.LL] lives in Germany. Spain has rejected such accusations,
stressing that nobody had caught the bacterium in Spain itself.
Doctors now suspect that a 40-year-old man who is in intensive care at
a San Sebastian hospital may have been infected with _E. coli_ (EHEC).
It was, however, deemed possible that the man had not caught the
bacterium in Spain, since he had returned recently from a trip to
Germany and the Czech Republic. A Spanish athlete is also being
treated for an EHEC infection in the German city of Hamburg, where she
participated in a marathon.

At a European Union agriculture ministers' meeting in Hungary on Tue
31 May 2011, Spain was preparing to seek financial compensation for
the damage the _E. coli_ outbreak had caused to its vegetable exports,
which have become virtually paralyzed to Central Europe and Russia.

In addition to Germany, there have been almost 4 dozen EHEC cases
reported in 5 other European countries, Austria, Britain, Denmark, the
Netherlands, and Sweden, with another 3 found in the USA. All have so
far only involved people who recently were in Germany or German
nationals travelling abroad.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[This is the 1st report of possible cases in Spain, Austria, Britain,
Netherlands & USA, all apparently acquired in Germany. No information
is seemingly available regarding the USA cases such as their location
and severity. More is likely to be forthcoming since the USA has just
finished a 3 day holiday weekend. - Mod.LL]

******
[6] France: suspected cases
Date: Sat 28 May 2011
Source: Romandie News, Agence France-Presse (AFP) report [in French,
machine trans. edited]
http://www.romandie.com/news/n/_FranceIntoxication_concombres__3_cas_suspects_en_cours_d_investigation280520111805.asp


The Ministries of Economy, Health and Agriculture announced in a
joint statement on Sat 28 May 2011, 3 suspected cases of _E. coli_
O104 infection linked to an outbreak in Germany due to bacteria found
in cucumbers, are under investigation in France.

It was announced that a batch of cucumbers considered suspicious was
delivered into French territory, but that the withdrawal from the
markets was immediately requested.

--
Communicated by:
HealthMap Alerts via ProMED-mail
