[No specific information is given regarding these cases especially
if, like all the other extra-German cases, the individuals acquired
the infection within Germany. - Mod.LL]

******
[7] Switzerland: suspected cases ex Germany
Date: Sat 28 May 2011
Source: 20 minutes online [in French, machine trans. edited]
http://www.20min.ch/ro/news/suisse/story/Un-deuxi-me-cas-en-Suisse-29469327


In Switzerland, a woman who recently traveled in northern Germany was
suffering from diarrhea, probably caused by EHEC, the Federal Office
of Public Health (BAG) said Fri 27 May 2011. She had eaten salad at a
meal after which other guests fell ill in Germany. She suffered no
further complications. Analysis of a 2nd and a 3rd case of infection
in Switzerland is currently underway to determine if it is the same
serotype of bacteria responsible for the deaths in Germany. The
results should be presented next week, said Daniel Koch of the Federal
Health Office (BAG) to [the news agency] ATS.

--
Communicated by:
HealthMap Alerts via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Animal faecal contamination of growing fruit and vegetables is known
to be an important source of enterohemorrhagic _E. coli_ (EHEC)
infections. It will be of particular interest to discover the source
of contamination in the current event. If initial reports of possible
involvement of organic produce are confirmed, this will lead to the
need to re-evaluate the application of animal-derived fertilizers
(such as organic manure) and requirements for their treatment in
organic agriculture. - Mod.AS]
